{"title_page": "Ye Zhemin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Ye (surname)|Ye]]}}\n[[File:Ye Zhemin.jpg|thumb|Ye Zhemin at his graduation from Peking University]]\n'''Ye Zhemin''' ({{zh|s=\u53f6\u5586\u6c11|t=\u8449\u5586\u6c11}}; 1924 \u2013 2 January 2018), also romanized as '''Yeh Che-min''',<ref name=\"KerrNeedham2004\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mabcHwmAD5oC&pg=PA158|title=Science and Civilisation in China|last1=Kerr|first1=Rose|last2=Needham|first2=Joseph|last3=Wood|first3=Nigel|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-521-83833-7|page=158}}</ref> was a Chinese art historian and authority on the history of [[Chinese ceramics]] and [[Chinese calligraphy|calligraphy]]. He is credited with making a discovery that led to the identification of Qingliangsi as the kiln site for the rare [[Ru ware]] of the [[Song dynasty]]. His published works include the extensive ''History of Chinese Pottery and Porcelain''.\n\n== Life and career ==\nYe Zhemin was born in 1924 into a [[Manchu people|Manchu]] family that descended from the [[Qing dynasty]] poet [[Nalan Xingde]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1932003|title=\u6307\u660e\u6c5d\u7a91\u7a91\u5740\u7b2c\u4e00\u4eba\u53f6\u5586\u6c11\u8f9e\u4e16\uff0c\u66fe\u5728\u533b\u9662\u8d70\u9053\u63a5\u53d7\u6cbb\u7597\u5f15\u5173\u6ce8|author=Zhong He \u949f\u79be|date=2 January 2018|website=The Paper|language=zh|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref> His father, Ye Linzhi \u53f6\u9e9f\u8dbe, was a historian of Chinese ceramics who discovered the [[Ding ware]] kiln site. Ye studied history of ceramics with his father from a young age, and later attended [[Peking University]], where he studied art and calligraphy under [[Xu Beihong]], {{ill|Luo Fukan|zh|\u7f57\u590d\u582a}}, and [[Pu Xinyu]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter graduation from university, Ye worked at the [[Palace Museum]] ([[Forbidden City]]) for 16 years. He conducted research at many of China's ancient kiln sites with ceramics experts Chen Wanli \u9648\u4e07\u91cc, Sun Yingzhou \u5b59\u701b\u6d32, and {{ill|Feng Xianming|zh|\u51af\u5148\u94ed}}.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1978, Ye was transferred to {{ill|Central Academy of Arts and Crafts|zh|\u6e05\u534e\u5927\u5b66\u7f8e\u672f\u5b66\u9662}} (now Academy of Arts and Design, [[Tsinghua University]]) to teach history of Chinese ceramics and history of Chinese calligraphy. In the 1980s and 1990s, he also served as an adjunct professor at Peking University and the [[Central Academy of Fine Arts]], and taught as a visiting professor at more than 10 universities abroad.<ref name=\":0\" /> The lectures he gave in Europe were collectively published in the book ''Chinese Ceramics'' in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museocineseparma.org/en/pubblicazioni/15-pubblicazioni/169-chinese-ceramics|title=Chinese Ceramics|date=|website=Museum of Chinese Art and Ethnography|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Contributions ==\nIn 1977, while surveying the Qingliangsi archaeological site in [[Baofeng County]], [[Henan]], Ye found a [[sherd]] of pottery that was typical of [[Ru ware]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Ru ware is an extremely rare and precious type of pottery from the [[Song dynasty]], and scholars had spent decades searching for its kiln site. Ye brought the sherd to Guo Yanyi \u90ed\u6f14\u4eea at the [[Shanghai Institute of Ceramics]], who analyzed its chemical composition and determined that it was nearly identical to that of a known Ru ware plate in the collection of the Palace Museum. The discovery was published in 1985, and Ye proposed Qingliangsi as the probable kiln site for Ru ware. Later archaeological excavations confirmed his proposition.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nYe published more than 100 research papers and over 10 monographs.<ref name=\":0\" /> His ''History of Chinese Pottery and Porcelain'' (\u4e2d\u56fd\u9676\u74f7\u53f2, {{ISBN|9787108034151}}), originally published in 2006, provides an extensive history of Chinese ceramics with perspectives from archaeology.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Ellen|date=22 April 2013|title=Ceramics|journal=Oxford Bibliographies|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1093/obo/9780199920082-0053}}</ref> His other books include ''A General Overview of the History of Chinese Calligraphy'' (\u4e2d\u56fd\u4e66\u6cd5\u53f2\u901a\u8bba), ''A General Overview of the Pottery and Porcelain of the Sui, Tang, Song, and Yuan Dynasties'' (\u968b\u5510\u5b8b\u5143\u9676\u74f7\u901a\u8bba), ''Cizhou Ware of China'' (\u4e2d\u56fd\u78c1\u5dde\u7a91, 2009).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Death ==\nIn late November 2017, Ye was hospitalized in Beijing for an illness. When a scholar, who was a student of one of Ye's students, went to visit him at the hospital, he found that Ye was lying in bed in a hallway. He posted a picture on social media, which was widely circulated and raised an outcry in Chinese media against the maltreatment of a renowned scholar. The hospital later moved him into a room, but he died a little more than a month later on 2 January 2018, aged 93.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://art.people.com.cn/n1/2018/0103/c226026-29742678.html|title=\u6c5d\u7a91\u7a91\u5740\u53d1\u73b0\u8ba4\u5b9a\u7b2c\u4e00\u4eba\u53f6\u5586\u6c11\u901d\u4e16 \u4eab\u5e7494\u5c81|date=3 January 2018|website=People's Daily|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ye, Zhemin}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chinese art historians]]\n[[Category:Peking University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tsinghua University faculty]]\n[[Category:Peking University faculty]]\n[[Category:Central Academy of Fine Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:Manchu people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese historians]]\n[[Category:Historians from Beijing]]\n", "text_old": "{{